    # [Scene: Council Hall | Night]

    scene bg ch13_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Tense, staccato strings build under distant percussion]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low murmur; the rustle of paper; a phone camera shutter]
    "You are in the room because the town asked you to be. You thought you would be there to argue numbers and models, to wedge a small, sensible plan into a larger machine. You are here to be deliberate."
    "Instead, Tess's whisper becomes everyone’s voice."

    scene bg ch13_3be532_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A collective, audible intake—like a held breath finally leaving]
    "Your chest drops. The documents are filthy with ledger lines and legalese, but the stain is plain: clauses that favor investor returns over where people live. Escrow diversions. Contingency funds labeled in ways that move money away from community projects. Footnotes that read like doors closing."
    "You taste metal. The fluorescent light feels narrower, like a tube aimed through your spine."
    "Tess does not look at you. She stares at the screen as if at a person she cannot forgive. Her voice, when it comes, is small and brittle."
    show tess_omalley at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tess_omalley "I couldn't keep holding this. They—someone had to make it public."
    "You want to reach out to her, to steady something, but the hall has already split into halves: those whose faces are open with outrage, those whose jaws are set into the business of counting what is lost."
    hide tess_omalley

    scene bg ch13_3be532_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Phones buzzing; murmured plans assembling]
    show livia_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    livia_chen "This is a breach of privacy and process. There are legal channels—"
    "A shout cuts her. Rafi stands near the back, wet coat clinging to him like second skin. When he speaks it is not from a script."
    show rafi_gmez at right:
        zoom 0.7

    rafi_gmez "Legal channels didn't keep my dock from rotting! Legal channels didn't tell us whose families would be priced out!"
    "There is a chorus now. Voices overlap. Someone bangs a fist. The projection six rows away shows a clause labeled 'Relocation Trigger.' The label is a match thrown into dry grass."

    menu:
        "Step to the podium and demand answers":
            "You push through the crowd, palms slick, and throw your words like nets—technical, precise, impossibly human. For a moment the air opens and people listen."
        "Stay in your seat and watch Livia Chen handle the fallout":
            "You fold your hands into your coat and watch Livia Chen, measuring her like a tide. You let the room decide your words for you, and guilt sits like a rock in your throat."

    # --- merge ---
    "The scene continues with the projection splitting public from private and the town forming committees."
    "The projection splits public from private: lenders, contractors, letters of intent with caveats designed for immediate buyouts. For thirty seconds it feels like sunlight after fog—clarity. People form themselves into committees with faces. Someone starts organizing"
    "a march. You imagine repair crews repurposed into oversight teams, Rafi at the lead, Naomi calling out metrics like a litany that will save homes."
    "You let hope bloom for a breath. It is quick and hot and sharp."
    "Then phones start vibrating. Livia Chen’s assistant races to the side, whispering like an animal."
    "Livia Chen: (low, to her aide) 'What's happening?'"
    "Assistant: (urgent) 'They're pulling funding. Immediate notices. Some lenders are freezing disbursements pending 'clarity.''"
    "Livia Chen's face—so controlled moments ago—tightens. The smile hardens into a line of metal catching light. The hall's air goes from chemistry to weather."
    "You rise anyway. You speak because silence would be the same as surrender."
    show mara_kestrel at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_kestrel "If we can hold a covenant—legal protection for neighborhoods—if we can bind investment to environmental covenants—"
    "Livia Chen: (cutting in) 'We don't have time for more delays. If the funds stop now, the whole project crumbles. You understand that, don't you? It isn't black and white.'"

    mara_kestrel "I understand time and tactics. I also understand houses sink when they're priced out of their own streets."
    "Livia Chen: (voice like glass) 'And I understand that without a single overarching structure, half the town floods."
    "If you want to play lawyer and activist, do it outside the council chamber.'"
    "Your voice rises. So does hers. The room splits into a thunderclap of accusation and calm. Cameras angle. Tess looks small, a figure made of paper and resolve."
    hide livia_chen
    show tess_omalley at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tess_omalley "We made them choose; they chose profit. People should be able to see where the money goes."
    "Livia Chen: (exasperated, then contained) 'Public fury does not repair a seawall.'"

    "The exchange ricochets. More phones. Call notifications—text" "Funds frozen."
    # [Scene: Flooded Promenade | Night]
    hide rafi_gmez
    hide mara_kestrel
    hide tess_omalley

    scene bg ch13_3be532_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Percussive loop, faster; low brass underpins a mounting howl]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Horns overseas, the slap of rain beginning against tarps]
    "The town reacts with the ferocity of a tide. Rafi organizes logistics with the practiced hands of someone who knows rope knots better than legalese. Grandpa Hira hums but louder now, a sound meant to steady. People who have never met each other trade keys and carabiners like currency."
    "For a fleeting beat, the town becomes a body moving together—repair crews at work, hand-in-hand sandbag lines forming, the greenhouse's pumps redirecting water. The energy is incandescent and dangerous: anger propelling action."
    "You think: maybe this is enough."
    "Then a call pierces the night—your phone, Tess's number lighting. The voice on the other end is clipped, rehearsed. It is Livia Chen’s office."

    "Dispatch" "Major backers are issuing withdrawal clauses. They're invoking force majeure related to reputational risk. Contractors will not proceed without cleared funds."
    "The words are deliberate hammers. The rhythm of community labor stumbles."
    "You rally people with the skills you have—maps, a prioritized list of weak points—but the reality is now both legal and physical: without guarantors, the supply lines dry. The scaffolding companies won't deliver metal without payment"
    "secured. The pumps are rented, but rental contracts rely on the money that just vanished."
    "You taste the iron tang of panic."

    menu:
        "Coordinate a localized, improvised reinforcement with volunteers":
            "You shout orders and scavenging becomes a choreography—old beams, buoyant pontoon barrels, a jury-rigged splice that might hold. Your hands blister but your voice is steady enough to keep hope moving."
        "Try to bring Tess and Livia Chen together to force a pause and renegotiate public guarantees":
            "You drag paperwork into the rain and stand between two powers. Livia Chen's jaw goes tight. Tess's face is a mask. For a moment negotiation is possible—then the contractors file an injunction."

    # --- merge ---
    "The scene continues as legal threats bloom and the weather answers the bureaucracy."
    "Legal threats bloom. Letters arrive like clouds: litigation threatened, liens placed, emergency injunctions filed. You watch as the abstract architecture of contracts becomes the real architecture of failure. An outside contractor—one of the only crews willing"
    "to work on short notice—accepts an emergency contract but with a caveat: margin clauses that let them walk at the first hint of nonpayment."
    "The weather answers the bureaucracy with immediate force. The first heavy wind of early season arrives on schedule, a wild breath that smells of distant cold and seaweed."
    # [Scene: Ruined Promenade | Night]

    scene bg ch13_3be532_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Full orchestra of chaos—string crescendos, dissonant brass, and a pounding timpani pulse]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The scream of wind, the crack of failing timber, the roar of water entering hollows]
    "The contractor's emergency reinforcement buckles with a sound like an animal giving up. First a fracture, then a wash. The barricade holds for a beat long enough for someone to scream a prayer and then collapses."
    "Water finds alleys you didn't think it would reach. It comes with a gust of wet cold, fingers grasping at shoes and furniture. The flood line climbs past thresholds you have marked as safe on your"
    "notebooks. The models you made—those precise, tight equations—eat the numbers of the present and spit them out as lies."
    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan is there in the center of it all, goggles cracked across his forehead, salt-smeared. He has been working like a person trying to outrun a clock. Now he stands with his shoulders squared to the water, a monument to exhausted hope."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "We'd patched so much with ideas and elbow grease. We didn't have the money to finish the things that mattered."
    "You move to him. His hands smell of oil and wet metal. He catches your wrist; his grip is a contained thing—grief and refusal braided together."
    show mara_kestrel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_kestrel "We exposed it. We thought sunlight would burn the rot away."
    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan: (bitter laugh, half swallowed) 'Sunlight burned the ledger. It scalded the investors. They left. The rot spread faster when we weren't prepared for the fallout.'"

    mara_kestrel "This isn't—this isn't only on us. They hid terms. Tess made it public because no one else would."
    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan: (voice breaking) 'There are reasons for being cautious. There are reasons for playing the long game. You knew that. You led with haste.'"
    "You feel the accusation like a physical blow. It is not just in his words; it is in the way the town looks at you now—faces stricken, eyes searching for a cause to blame."
    "A council member points across the water. 'Mara Kestrel's team — they bypassed approvals last spring. If not for them—'"
    "A neighbor spits the rest into the wind. 'They started it. They made Livia Chen act so fast. Now look.'"
    "Livia Chen stands framed by flood lamps, her expression split open—betrayal, panic, and the metallic glint of someone who has decided that softness is a liability. Her leadership, recently secure, shatters into a dozen sharp choices."
    "Livia Chen: (hard, ruthless) 'Evacuate the lower quarter. We will enact emergency controls. No more debates while people flood.'"
    "Her hand is on a radio; orders snap into the air. Volunteers shout back, tired and angry. Soldiers of policy move like vectors—decisions falling into place like dominos. Her voice has the authority of a person"
    "who has taken the only route that promises survival for some at the expense of many."
    "Mara Kestrel: (to Livia Chen) 'If you lock people out—if you lock neighborhoods to save others—do you know what you are doing to the fabric of this town?'"
    show livia_chen at right:
        zoom 0.7

    livia_chen "You're asking me to choose between impossible harms. I am doing the only thing I can within the constraints we have."
    "Her eyes meet yours for a fraction of a second—no softness, only a raw, owned calculation. For the first time you see something like shame ghost across her features. Then it hardens. She issues another order."
    "The town fractures like coastal stone struck again and again. Small boats shove off. People fold possessions into zipped bags. A child looks back at a splintered cafe and begins to cry; the sound is thin and suddenly everyone is listening."
    "You clasp Elias 'Eli' Rowan's hand because you have few solid anchors left. He squeezes back—firm, patient, terrified in a way that turns your stomach. Around you, neighbors lower small wooden dinghies into the black water. The harbor lights refract into a thousand broken points."
    "Rafi shouts to you over the roar. 'Get people to the pier! Don't let them board alone!'"

    "You move, voice hoarse from shouting, issuing practical instructions you have practiced in calm rooms. You hand out life vests. Your fingers smell of diesel and fear. Someone tries to blame you outright into a camera. You hear it" "You started this. You put the town at risk."
    "Those words rub like salt into the fresh wounds. There are faces you have loved in that accusation."
    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan: (soft, barely audible) 'There's nowhere left to hide, Mara Kestrel.'"
    "Mara Kestrel: (the admission is a hard stone) 'I don't know if I can—'"

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "You don't have to hide. You can stand. Right here. With me."
    "He holds your hand until the grip goes slack in the tide and then tightens again. It is small and terrible and the only warmth you can find. Around you, small boats nose out into the oily water, lights bobbing away like drowned constellations."
    "You watch them go. You hear names called—neighbors, friends—one after another. The sound of doors closing behind people you served, people you loved. The town's edges blur. The promontory the boardwalk once traced is now a jagged bruise of broken planks and flotsam."
    "Tess is there on the quay, drenched, eyes rimmed red. She is not triumphant; the leak has not delivered justice. It has delivered accelerated collapse."
    "Tess: (to you, raw) 'I thought it would wake them up. I thought we could force a better plan.'"

    mara_kestrel "It woke them. It woke them fast. But waking doesn't pay for reinforcement."
    "Tess looks away—helplessness finally wearing her face. The camera lights of local press swing and then go dark as crews pull their vans away; the legal machinery takes over like a tide you cannot swim against."
    "You have no script out of this. There is no neat accountability that will right what you feel has been done and undone. Lenders have frozen lines. Contractors are suing. The town's cohesion is unstitched."
    hide mara_kestrel
    hide livia_chen

    scene bg ch13_3be532_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single, sustained minor chord falls into silence, then a low, inexorable drone]
    "You had thought exposure would be a scalpel. Instead it has been a blowtorch that burned liabilities and support alike. The public honesty you and Tess deployed has not saved New Aster. It hastened fracture, accelerated withdrawal, and gave everyone the clean outrage they needed to wash their hands."
    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan: (a whisper) 'Where do we go from here?'"
    "Mara Kestrel: (feel the weight of all the models, the people, the promises) 'We—'"
    "You cannot finish the word because the harbor has become an exit and a wound at once. Boats pull away in a slow procession, lights blinking like last breaths. People you know wave from decks, faces small and remote."
    "Rafi slaps your shoulder with a force that is more plea than anger."
    show rafi_gmez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rafi_gmez "Don't let the blame be the last thing we say to each other."
    "Mara Kestrel: (your throat raw) 'I don't want it to be.'"
    "The rain is a steady percussion now. It tastes of iron and old stories. The town's shape changes while you watch—some places already caved into the sea, others standing like unfinished sentences."
    "You press your forehead to Elias 'Eli' Rowan's shoulder and let the salt on your face mix with the rain. There is grief, thick and precise as a map of losses. There is also an unbearable,"
    "intimate shame: that your act to reveal truth may have unravelled the only tether New Aster had to outside funding, and that the unraveling moves as quickly as water."
    hide rafi_gmez

    scene bg ch13_3be532_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Dissonant chord resolves into a low, aching tone]
    "You stand at the water's edge and watch your town’s people leave in stages—some by boat, some by packed trucks rumbling down the coastal road. The air tastes of diesel, wet cloth, and loss."
    "Your role in this unspooling sits on your shoulders as if it were a coat too heavy to carry. You cannot see a path that won't carve new wounds to prevent others. The knowledge that exposure"
    "did not save you but hastened a breakdown loops and loops in your head, a record stuck on the same sorrowful note."
    "You let go of Elias 'Eli' Rowan's hand only when the last boat is far enough away that sound becomes memory. He turns to you, eyes bright beneath the brim of his wet cap."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "We did what we thought was right."
    "Mara Kestrel: (the certainty of it is brittle) 'We did. And it tore things.'"
    "He doesn't answer because there is nothing to say that can mend the present. Instead, he pulls you into the shelter of his coat and lets the rain run down both your backs."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant engines fade. The rain keeps time. A siren wails far off—an emergency measure, not a rescue.]

    scene bg ch13_3be532_8 at full_bg
    "When the boats are gone, the maps are re-drawn by absence. The boardwalk is a wound. The council chamber is a stage for recrimination. Livia Chen's authority is splintered and hardened; she will enact measures, and"
    "they will save some and cost others. Tess will carry a new shame that mixes with her conviction. Rafi will hold what he can. Naomi will keep telling you exactly what the numbers mean, cold and"
    "unbending."
    "You will carry this night like a stone in your mouth—forever altering the sound of your speech."
    "You do not walk away from the shore that night, but there is no literal, neat resolution—only the finality of departure. The town fractures in ways that will not be undone by apologies or data. You are left with the raw architecture of consequence."
